{
  "doc_id": "56712",
  "text": "Iyengar [CITATION_1] presented genetic heuristic algorithms and solves the k-anonymity problem using an incomplete stochastic search method. The method does not assure the quality of the solution proposed, but experimental results show the validity of the approach. Winkler [CITATION_2] proposed a method based on simulated annealing for finding locally minimal solutions, which requires high computational time and does not assure the quality of the solution. Fung, Wang and Yu [CITATION_3] presented a topdown heuristic to make a table to be released k-anonymous. The algorithm starts from the most general solution, and iteratively specializes some values of the current solution until the k-anonymity requirement is violated. Each step of specialization increases the information and decreases the anonymity.",
